  "script": "A heat dome is parking over the West, and it's turning whole forests into kindling. A heat dome is exactly what it sounds like: a giant lid of high pressure that traps hot air and bakes the same region for days. The ground dries out, the brush turns to tinder, and all it takes is one spark. Once a fire starts in that heat, it doesn't crawl, it runs, throwing embers a mile ahead to start new fires before crews can even reach the first one. Temperatures are smashing records, and the danger doesn't drop at night anymore. Firefighters call these the conditions that make a fire explode. So how do you stop a fire that's making its own weather?",
